                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc form="Codex">
                            <supportDesc material="parchment">
                                <support>
                                    <material key="parchment">Parchment</material> book block.</support>
                                <extent>246 folios: <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                                        <height>365</height>
                                        <width>325</width>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </extent>
                                <foliation>
                                    <p>Modern pencil foliation in Arabic numerals on the upper right corner of each recto folio.</p>
                                </foliation>
                                <collation><p>No consistent quire structure (between 3-5 bifolia per section) and made-up sections of single folios with stubs (guarded in).</p></collation>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout columns="3" writtenLines="26">
                                    <p>Three columns, 26 lines per leaf.</p>
                                    <p>Folios have been pricked and scored to assist in writing.</p>
                                </layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc hands="3">
                            <handNote  xml:id="h2" scope="major" script="Ethiopic" medium="ink">
                                <p>Written in a <term>Ge'ez</term> script, in black and red ink. Two hands copied <locus from="1r" to="203v">1r-203v</locus>.</p></handNote>
                          <handNote xml:id="h3" scope="minor" script="Ethiopic" medium="ink">
                                <p>A third hand copied <locus from="204r" to="245v">204r-245v</locus> in a <term type="script">Ge'ez</term> script.</p>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                        <additions>
                            <p>Rubrics were added in the upper margin on <locus from="124v" to="124v">124v</locus> and throughout concerning the different events of the Passion.</p>
                            <p>Prayers were added on <locus from="200v" to="201r">200v-201r</locus>.</p>
                            <p>An excerpted text from ሉቃስ (Luke) 24:13-32 was added on <locus from="202r" to="202r">202r</locus>.</p>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="unknown" notBefore="1687" notAfter="1687">
                                <p>Ethiopic binding. Full bound in brown leather with blind tooled decoration. Wooden boards, thick and coarsely cut with a slight rounding of the three
                                    external edges. Rebacked with new leather covering the spine, a quarter of the front and back boards and turn in squares. Leather is not adhered directly to the
                                    spine, but is secured at head and tail by endband structure. Brown leather split braid endbands, though tailband has slipped down the spine slightly. Large turn ins
                                    and red velvet inner board lining. Unsupported sewing at 4 stations (two even pairs of sewing stations). The sewing is laced into the boards as an integral part of
                                    the sewing process and is done in separate pairs with each pair sewn using a different thread.</p>
                                <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                                        <height>373</height>
                                        <width>339</width>
                                        <depth>111</depth>
                                    </dimensions></p>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <origDate calendar="gregorian" when="1687"  cert="high">1687</origDate>
                            <origPlace><country ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000489">Ethiopia</country></origPlace></origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>A marginal note on <locus from="3r" to="3r">3r</locus> indicates the book belonged to the Church of the Saviour of the World located at <placeName
                                    ref="LOC0000">Āmba Maryam</placeName> (i.e. Magdala): ግብረ ፡ ሕማማት ፡ ዘቅዱስ ፡ መድኃኔ ፡ ዓለም.</p>
                          <p>On <locus from="200v" to="200v">200v</locus> a note indicates the book belonged to St George's Church (in <placeName ref="LOC0000"
                                    >Gondar</placeName>?).</p>
                            <p>A label on the inner upper cover mentions an officer from the British Army: 'G. F. Robertson, Lieut.
                                and Adjutant, 3rd Dragoon Guards, Magdala, 13 April 1868'.</p>
                          <p>The following ownership names are mentioned: <name role="fmo"><persName ref="PRS0000">Ledätawit</persName></name> (<locus from="216v" to="216v">216v</locus>); <name
                            role="fmo"><persName ref="PRS0000">Yohannes</persName></name> (<locus from="218v" to="218v">218v</locus>); <name role="fmo"><persName ref="PRS0000">Wäldä
                              Abib</persName></name> and <name role="fmo"><persName ref="PRS0000">Wälättä Petros</persName></name> (<locus from="245v" to="245v">245v</locus>).</p>
                            <p>On <locus from="199v" to="199v">199v</locus>: A note ascribing the present work to the Metropolitian <name type="person" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/284826324" role="aut"
                              ><persName ref="PRS0000">Abuna Salama</persName></name>: ወዘአጽሐፋ ፡ እንከ ፡ አቡነ ፡ ክቡር ፡ ወዓቢይ ፡ ... አባ ፡ ሰላማ ፡ ጳጳስ ፡ ዘብሔረ ፡ (c) አግዓዚ ፡ ….</p>
                            <p><locus from="199v" to="200r">199v-200r</locus>: A benediction for ዓፅፈ፡ ክርስቶስ ('Āḍfa Krestos), who commissioned the book.</p>
                        </provenance>
                      <provenance><p><name type="person" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420" role="fmo"><persName ref="PRS0000">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847-1913)</persName>
                                    </name>. The inner upper cover
                                (pastedown) bears the armorial bookplate (Ex Libris) identifying the codex as having once been part of the Bibliotheca Lindesiana, the private library of the Lindsay
                                family, Earls of Crawford and Balcarres | Armorial bookplate (Ex Libris): ARMS: Quarterly, 1st and 4th,
                                Gules a fess chequy Argent and Azure; 2nd and 3rd, Or a lion rampant Gules, debruised of a ribbon in bend Sable. CREST: a swan’s head, neck, and wings proper, issuing
                                from an antique ducal coronet Or. SUPPORTERS: two lions, rampant guardant Gules. MOTTO in Latin: Endure fort (Endure bravely) | Bibliotheca Lindesiana | pencilled:
                                5/G.</p>
                        </provenance>
                      <provenance><p>Purchased by <name type="person" role="fon"><persName ref="PRS0000">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName>Enriqueta Rylands,
                                        1843-1908</name> in <date calendar="gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford
                            (1847-1913).</p></provenance>
                        <acquisition><p>Bequeathed by Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908) in <date calendar="gregorian" when="1908">1908</date> to <name type="institution"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/152274029" role="own"><orgName type="display">The John Rylands Library</orgName></name>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
